pred: SUMMARY: The dinosaur problem was a highlight of the lecture for many students, who found it engaging and challenging to solve. They appreciated the opportunity to work in breakout rooms and use substitution to find the time when two dinosaurs with different accelerations would meet. Students enjoyed the process of setting the equations equal to each other and determining which equation to use. The problem allowed them to apply the kinematic equations to a real-world scenario, making the concept more tangible and interesting. The dinosaur problem also helped students understand how to combine accelerations in relative motion and visualize the motion of the dinosaurs, with some students noting the clever use of negative signs to simplify the equation. Overall, the dinosaur problem was a fun and interactive way for students to apply their knowledge of kinematics and problem-solving skills.

pred: SUMMARY: Students found the concept of vector addition to be interesting, particularly the method of breaking vectors into components to solve problems. Many appreciated the use of visual aids, such as triangles and diagrams, to facilitate understanding. The idea of adding vectors by combining their components and the concept of subtracting vectors by adding their negative counterparts were also well-received. Students enjoyed the interactive approach to learning, including the use of Top Hat questions and breakout rooms, which allowed them to work in groups and discuss their ideas. The application of vector addition to real-world scenarios, such as the hockey and yeti problems, was also seen as engaging and thought-provoking. Overall, students appreciated the clear and step-by-step approach to teaching vector addition, which helped to clarify their understanding of the concept.
input:
The format. I've never had a flipped class like this one so it was unusual to have the small time for review and then immediately in to problem solving. I've also never heard vector addition described with the principle of moving backwards along one arrow and that that's why you subtract it (rather than in reference to the idea that origin doesn't matter and therefore whatever the starting location is should be subtracted out from every piece)

I think the most interesting part was the use of break out rooms to allow the students to collaborate on a problem

pred: SUMMARY: Students generally found the lecture on vector math to be clear and easy to follow, but some struggled with specific concepts such as determining when to use sine or cosine, understanding the direction of resultant vectors, and subtracting vectors. Many students expressed confusion about the rules for adding and subtracting vectors, including when to add 180 degrees to an angle and how to determine the direction of a resultant vector. Some students also struggled with visualizing vectors, including drawing vectors from head to tail and understanding the relationship between vectors and their components. Additionally, a few students mentioned difficulty with unit vectors, including understanding their purpose and how to use them in calculations.

Many students appreciated the "recipe" for drawing FBDs, which made the process easier, and enjoyed the conceptual questions that required critical thinking. Overall, the interactive and problem-solving nature of FBDs, including the use of Top Hat questions and breakout rooms, was well-received by the students.

pred: SUMMARY: Students found the discussion on carbon emissions to be a highlight of the lecture, with many expressing interest in learning about their personal carbon footprint and the environmental impact of their daily activities. The calculation of CO2 emissions from vehicles, particularly the example of the Corolla producing 260 grams of CO2 per mile, was a striking revelation for many. The use of online tools and websites to estimate and visualize carbon footprints also generated significant interest. Additionally, the concept of design trade-offs and its relation to carbon emissions was well-received, with students appreciating the importance of considering environmental factors in engineering design. Overall, the topic of carbon emissions resonated with students, sparking curiosity and concern about their individual and collective impact on the environment.

input:
Today's class was little confusing and I didn't need any extra details.
Prototyping 
The prototype section, specifically testing, is VERY confusing. My team is unsure how we are supposed to test our prototypes, especially if they are created using CAD software. Without purchasing materials, I'm unsure what could be used to create and test our solutions.
How detailed we need to be in our prototypes. 
Finding ways to develop a prototype for our idea 
I was confused about how to make a prototype for one of our designs originally. 
Nothing was confusing in today's class
I didn't get what materials i should use for prototype 
Something that could use more details in today's class was the schedule with our new reading day, because you went over it kind of quick and I didn't catch all the dates. 
We as a team found it difficult to find out not only how we would build a prototype, and how to test it. Unless we make them individually, physical prototypes aren't really feasible due to our separation. Additionally we couldn't figure out doable but also reliable ways to test our prototypes. 
 I thought the most difficult aspect of today's class was determining how to prototype our ideas to show the functionality of them.
 How we should develop a testing protocol is unclear. I don't remember going over it in the video modules and it isn't explained in the technical brief or assignment 17 instructions. I think going through an example of a testing protocol for the smart recycling bins would have been beneficial to the teams' understanding of what a testing protocol is and how to develop an effective one. 
 The confusing part about today was figuring out how my group will make the prototypes and test them in life. This was confusing for us because one of our team members is off campus, so we need to figure out how to test the prototypes and how we are making them.
 Everything made sense into today's class. But I wish there was more explanation to the ways we could create prototypes if the software option was not available to use. Other than that, everything made sense.
 I found it interesting the different types of modeling that could be used
 What was confusing was how the prototypes the groups create will be tested. My group was having a hard time understanding how this would be done virtually and with models of our design (given we don't have the ability to make real models of our prototype with the materials we wanted)
 The details for the assignment was confusing to me. The team was confused on what CAD software to use and some of the other elements of the assignment. I think after the slides are posted we will be able to review it and answer our questions.
 A confusing thing was the building of prototypes. It was confusing because of the use of materials that aren't easily accessible. 
 I am unsure of when A18 is due because bright space still has it down for next Friday. But it was said that we will work on it next Friday in class as well.
 I think prototyping in general is a bit confusing, at least to me. I dont really know how should I approach prototype making.

 How we can test our ideas was confusing because our ideas must be used on such a large sclae and we have such limited materials.
 I did not completely understand how through our prototypes had to be.
 Nothing was confusing or hard to understand. Everything was very clear 
 I haven't been exposed to a lot of the prototyping methods like CAD, so I feel like it might be pretty tough to learn something like that in the next week. 
 I thought it was confusing when we talked about the surveys because I was unsure if they counted as part of the prototype testing process. 
 I wasn't confused about anything today. We just had a few hiccups with our last grade and discussed with the TA what we got wrong.

 How we should go about testing any physical model that we create

 I am confused on how to exactly test my virtual prototypes. 
 Knowing how to prototype virtually can be difficult and confusing at times, and having useful accessible materials is not always possible.
